 SQLCODE , SQLERRM :- 
 ====================

   SQLCODE  => returns error code
   SQLERRM  => returns error message

  => sqlcode is useful to handle errors that are not having names

 Ex :- 

 CREATE TABLE emp55
 (
  empno NUMBER(4) PRIMARY KEY,
  ename VARCHAR2(10) NOT NULL,
  sal  NUMBER(8) CHECK(sal>=5000)
  );

 wap to insert data into emp55 table ?

 DECLARE
     veno  emp55.empno%TYPE;
     vname  emp55.ename%TYPE;
     vsal  emp55.sal%TYPE;
 BEGIN
      veno := &empno;
      vname := '&ename' ;
      vsal  := &sal;
      INSERT INTO emp55 VALUES(veno,vname,vsal);
      COMMIT;
  EXCEPTION
        WHEN  DUP_VAL_ON_INDEX THEN
               DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('empno should not be duplicate');
        WHEN OTHERS THEN
                IF SQLCODE = -02290 THEN
                    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('sal >= 5000');
               END IF;
 END;
  /

USER DEFINED EXCEPTIONS :- 
============================

 => exceptions raised by user are called user defined exceptions 
 => user must raise exception to stop program execution based on some condition
 => the following built-ins are used to raise exception

     1   RAISE stmt
     2   RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR

 using RAISE stmt :- 
 ================

      RAISE  <exception-name> ; 

Ex  :- 

      RAISE  abc ;

  => exception "abc" must be declared in declaration part

         abc   EXCEPTION ;

 
   DECLARE
     a  NUMBER(3);
     b  NUMBER(3);
     c  NUMBER(3);
     ONE_DIVIDE   EXCEPTION;
 BEGIN
     a := &a;
     b := &b;
     IF b=1 THEN
          RAISE ONE_DIVIDE;
      END IF;
     c := a/b;
     DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(c);
 EXCEPTION
    WHEN ZERO_DIVIDE THEN
        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('divisor cannot be zero');
   WHEN ONE_DIVIDE THEN
       DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('divisor cannot be one');
   WHEN OTHERS THEN
        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(SQLERRM);
  END;
 /

using RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR :-
---------------------------------------------------------

        RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR(error code , error msg);

              error code  =>  -20001 to -20999
   
 Ex :- 

   => wap to input empno and increment sal but sunday updates are  not allowed ? 

     DECLARE
        veno  emp.empno%TYPE;
        vamt  NUMBER(5);
    BEGIN
        veno := &empno;
        vamt := &amount; 
         IF  TO_CHAR(sysdate,'fmday') = 'sunday' THEN 
                   RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR(-20001,'sunday not allowed');
         END IF;
        UPDATE emp SET sal = sal + vamt WHERE empno = veno;
        COMMIT;
  END;
     /


difference between raise & raise_application_error  ?

  1   in raise exception is raised by using name
       in raise_application_error exception is raised by using error code

 2    to raise exception and to handle exception then use raise statement
       to raise exception and do not want to handle it then use raise_application_error 

